Question

A sinusoidal wave is graphed below.


Estimate the amplitude of the sinusoidal function graphed above.

Solution

The amplitude of a sinusoidal function is half the difference between the maximum \(y\) and the minimum \(y\).


\[A~=~\frac{(-1.1)-(-4.3)}{2} ~=~ \frac{3.2}{2} ~=~ 1.6\]

The amplitude is 1.6.

This exact function could be plotted with the following algebraic definition: \[y(t) = 1.6 \sin\left(\frac{2\pi}{2.4}(t+0.4)\right)+(-2.7)\]

The amplitude is 1.6; the period is 2.4; the horizontal shift is left by 0.4; and the midline is \(y=-2.7\).
